<!--
  Spike attribute-map: decode the attributes mocksaml (ory/boxyhq) actually
  releases. Verified against a real signed assertion driven end to end:
  mocksaml emits exactly four attributes, all with
  NameFormat="urn:oasis:names:tc:SAML:2.0:attrname-format:unspecified" and plain
  (non-URI) Names, plus a NameID in emailAddress format:

      Name="id"        -> id="uid"        (sha256 of the email)
      Name="email"     -> id="email"      (also the NameID value)
      Name="firstName" -> id="firstName"
      Name="lastName"  -> id="lastName"

  The STOCK /etc/shibboleth/attribute-map.xml only maps OID/URI-named attributes
  (urn:oid:..., urn:mace:...), so it dropped all four silently -> the SP extracted
  nothing -> REMOTE_USER was empty -> the authorizer exported no identity. This
  file (mounted over the stock one) is the fix.

  How the identity reaches the app: the FastCGI shibauthorizer exports each
  decoded attribute (and REMOTE_USER) as an HTTP RESPONSE header named
  "Variable-<id>" (e.g. Variable-email, Variable-REMOTE_USER). Traefik's
  ForwardAuth then copies the header names listed in the Middleware's
  authResponseHeaders onto the upstream request. So the id chosen here IS the
  header suffix the app receives.

  Operator note: this map is generated per-IdP from the attribute contract the
  IdP advertises. A real federation (InCommon) IdP emits urn:oid:-named,
  SCOPED attributes (eppn, eduPersonScopedAffiliation) -> those additionally need
  a non-default attribute-policy.xml (the stock policy's ScopingRules reject
  '@'-bearing values). mocksaml's flat attributes dodge that; a real IdP will not.
-->
<Attributes xmlns="urn:mace:shibboleth:2.0:attribute-map"
            xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance">
    <Attribute name="email"     id="email"/>
    <Attribute name="firstName" id="firstName"/>
    <Attribute name="lastName"  id="lastName"/>
    <Attribute name="id"        id="uid"/>
</Attributes>
